description.narrative: (Kenya): The Academic Model Providing Access to Healthcare (AMPATH Plus) activity strengthens health systems and improves family planning, reproductive, maternal, newborn, child, and adolescent health in Uasin Gishu county. Major activities include support to voluntary family; postnatal care; promotion of healthy spacing of births; emergency obstetric and newborn care; antenatal care; postnatal care for mother and newborn; prevention and case management of diarrhea and pneumonia at facility and community levels; and routine immunization and maternal nutrition. The project will train health facility and community health volunteers to increase technical capacity; strengthen health information systems and supply chain systems for essential medical commodities; and enhance monitoring and supervision systems. In addition, the projects will support water, sanitation and hygiene services with special focus on rural Community Led Total Sanitation (CLTS) and increased access to safe drinking water. Utilizing a health systems strengthening approach is a key element to ensure sustainability upon project completion, which is vital to achieving the Kenya Integrated Country Strategy Goal 3, and U.S Department of State and USAID Joint Strategic Plan 2018-2022 objective 2.2 "Promote healthy, educated and productive populations in partner countries to drive inclusive and sustainable development, open new markets and support U.S. prosperity and security objectives" Improving global public health supports the Administration's priority of asserting U.S. leadership and influence.
